				\begin{document}$$^2\Pi _{3/2}$$\end{document} ground state are strong due to the maser effect in O-CSEs, in particular the 1612 MHz line, and hence enables observations of objects at large distances. However, the maser effect causes a problem, since observed line brightnesses are not easily (and reliably) converted into quantitative measures of, e.g., the mass-loss rate. Instead OH maser emission mass-loss-rate estimates are based on the fact that the size of the emitting OH shell depends on the mass-loss rate (circumstellar OH is a photodissociation product of H2O\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {H}_2\hbox {O}$$\end{document}), and the OH luminosity for a saturated maser depends on the size of the OH shell. Hence, there is a relation between mass-loss rate and OH maser luminosity. Using this, relations between OH flux densities and mass-loss rate have been derived (e.g., Baud and Habing 1983). Mass-loss-rate estimates based on such relations are believed to provide order of magnitude estimates. OH line emission has the obvious disadvantage of not providing mass-loss-rate estimates for C-CSEs. The method has been used extensively over the years, but in this review we will only discuss it in special contexts.

Dust emission can be divided into a broad continuum and sharper features (Δλ/λ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
