Spectral energy distribution (SED) estimate A safer approach is to use a coverage of the SED which is as broad as possible, and supplement this with a detailed radiative transfer model that may take into account additional complexities like multi-component dust, grain-size distribution, CSE morphology, etc. This is the most reliable of the empirical methods for obtaining dust-mass-loss-rate estimates, but it rests on a large number of assumptions; an obvious remaining problem is that the dust kinematics cannot be measured. Examples of SED fits are shown in Fig. 5. This method was applied by, e.g., Groenewegen et al. (2007) and Gullieuszik et al. (2012) to samples of stars. Because of the complex modelling it is normally not a good method for large samples, but the GRAMS grids4 for C-rich (Srinivasan et al. 2011) and O-rich (Sargent et al. 2011) objects have been used in such contexts.Fig. 5
