It should be noted that Alvén-wave-driven winds require open flux tubes, radially directed away from the star, in order for the gas to be accelerated and escape. The present knowledge of magnetic field strengths and geometries in cool giants is very limited. To measure directly the magnetic field of an AGB star has turned out to be difficult, but a recent result on the S-star χ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\chi $$\end{document} Cyg, indicating a field strength of a few Gauss (Lèbre et al. 2014), suggests that major progress may be done in this area in the future. Magnetic field strength estimates in CSEs are based on maser lines of SiO, H2O\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {H}_2\hbox {O}$$\end{document}, and OH, and on “normal” line emission from CN through the Zeeman effect (Duthu et al. 2017) and from CO through the Goldreich-Kylafis effect (Vlemmings et al. 2012). The maser results are notoriously difficult to interpret, but they suggest (when extrapolated) magnetic field strengths in the range 100-2G\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$10^{0-2}\,\hbox {G}$$\end{document} and a radial dependence in between r-2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r^{-2}$$\end{document} (solar-type) and r-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r^{-1}$$\end{document} (toroidal) for M-stars (Vlemmings 2014). The CN results on C-rich objects are consistent with a stellar magnetic field strength of a few Gauss and a toroidal field (Duthu et al. 2017). The large-scale structure remains uncertain, but future observations of, e.g., the polarization of CO line emission with ALMA may make good progress here for AGB stars of all chemical types. The origin of the magnetic field of AGB stars is not known, but various possible mechanisms have been put forward (see, e.g., Vlemmings 2014). If magnetic fields play a role in the mass-loss process, one may expect a correlation between the wind properties (mass-loss rate, wind velocity) and the magnetic field strength, but such a correlation remains to be shown.

It is often assumed that the formation of an equatorial density enhancement, e.g., a disk, is an important step in this context. Indeed, the presence of a disk has been inferred in a number of post-AGB objects (Bujarrabal et al. 2013), while disks around AGB stars have remained elusive. However, clear evidence of a dust disk with an inner and outer edge lying at ≈6\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\approx \,6$$\end{document} and ≈13au\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\approx \,13\,\hbox {au}$$\end{document}, respectively, has recently been found towards the M-star L2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {L}_2$$\end{document} Pup (Kervella et al. 2015; Lykou et al. 2015; Ohnaka et al. 2015). This could be the first evidence of disk formation around a star at the end of its evolution on the AGB.

The picture that has emerged can be summarized as follows: The slow, massive winds of AGB stars, with typical mass loss rates of 10-7\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$10^{-7}$$\end{document}–10-5M⊙/year\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$10^{-5}\,\hbox {M}_{\odot }/\hbox {year}$$\end{document}, and above (see Sect. 3), are most likely triggered by a combination of pulsation-induced shock waves, creating favorable conditions for dust formation in the outer atmospheric layers, and the subsequent radiative acceleration of these newly-formed dust grains, which collide with the surrounding gas and drag it along (Sect. 4). Mid-IR spectroscopy and spectro-interferometry have made it possible to identify the chemical composition of circumstellar dust, and where different species originate. Combining these observations with results of dynamical atmosphere and winds models suggests that the winds of typical M-type AGB stars are driven by scattering of stellar photons on Fe-poor, Mg-rich silicate grains which start forming at around 2 stellar radii and grow to sizes in the range of 0.1–1 μm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\upmu \hbox {m}$$\end{document}, possibly on top of Al2O3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {Al}_2\hbox {O}_3$$\end{document} cores which condense even closer to the star (Sect. 4.2). The winds of C-type AGB stars, on the other hand, are generally assumed to be driven by radiation pressure on opaque amorphous carbon grains which produce significant circumstellar reddening but otherwise featureless IR spectra.

The gas CSE Rotational lines of CO will remain the best probe of the gas, and the standard CSE model will be tailored to fit an accurate radiative transfer treatment of this molecule. The physical model presently used dates back to the work of Goldreich and Scoville (1976) to a large extent. In particular, the treatment of the thermodynamics of the gas, and the chemistry of CO, its formation and subsequent photodissociation, needs to be updated, as well as observationally constrained. The initial abundance of CO with respect to H2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {H}_2$$\end{document}, determined by the chemistry in the extended stellar atmosphere, can possibly be directly estimated in some cases using UV absorption lines. The treatment of CO photodissociation has been updated since the work of Mamon et al. (1988), but it remains to be adapted to the special case of AGB CSEs. An inherent uncertainty in this context is the local interstellar radiation field, but observations with, e.g., ALMA will put constraints on the CO line brightness distributions. Another problem in this context is that other molecules may affect the thermodynamics of the gas through line cooling/heating of the gas, e.g., H2O\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {H}_2\hbox {O}$$\end{document} in O-CSEs and HCN in C-CSEs. This requires that both the chemistry and the radiative transfer of these molecules must be solved self-consistently together with the CO modelling. The physical conditions in the inner CSE, e.g., the acceleration zone, are expected to have only a small influence on the CO mass-loss-rate estimates as long as they are not dependent solely on higher-energy lines. Observations of the 21 cm line of HI can be used to firmly establish to what extent the estimated CO mass-loss rates must be corrected for the loss of also atomic gas.

